<subSubSection id="D6B76566FFC1570FA8E019DAC545FE76" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="9E1236EDFFC1570FA8E019DAC151FF31" blockId="11.[151,272,151,177]" box="[151,272,151,177]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<heading id="C55A8181FFC1570FA8E019DAC151FF31" bold="true" box="[151,272,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FA8E019DAC151FF31" box="[151,272,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Amerilini">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FA8E019DAC151FF31" bold="true" box="[151,272,151,177]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Amerilini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E1236EDFFC1570FA8E01992C545FE76" blockId="11.[151,1437,223,646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FA8E01992C1E5FF79" bold="true" box="[151,420,223,249]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnostic characters:</emphasis>
The species of a monogeneric tribe 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAB481992C3EDFF79" box="[831,940,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Amerilini">Amerilini</taxonomicName>
are medium to large sized (wingspan 
<quantity id="59559B08FFC1570FAD2C1992C085FE9E" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="24.5" valueMax="32.0" valueMin="17.0">17-32 mm</quantity>
) and quite robust, proboscis is particularly well developed, antennae are filiform in both sexes and the flagellum comprise 80 segments, forewings are elongated, comparatively narrow and often fully or partly transparent medially; hindwings are much shorter than forewings and generally weakly scaled (
<bibRefCitation id="FA3C4B1CFFC1570FAC391806C51CFEE5" author="Hauser, C. L. &amp; Boppre, M." box="[1102,1373,331,357]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 44" refId="ref64805" refString="Hauser, C. L. &amp; Boppre, M. (1997) A revision of the Afrotropical taxa of the genus Amerila Walker (Lepidoptera: Arctiidae). Systematic Entomology, 22 (1), 1 - 44. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1365 - 3113.1997. d 01 - 21. x" type="journal article" year="1997">Häuser &amp; Boppré 1997</bibRefCitation>
). The genus was traditionally included in the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAAF61822C299FE09" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[641,728,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctiini">Arctiini</taxonomicName>
based on its superficial similarity to some other tropical genera. However, modern phylogenetical studies based on genetic data provided the evidence that 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAC0918DEC499FE2D" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1855" box="[1150,1240,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAC0918DEC499FE2D" box="[1150,1240,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Amerila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather constitutes a sister group to the Syntomini+ 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAA7118FAC21EFE51" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[518,607,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctiini">Arctiini</taxonomicName>
clade formally proposed as the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAC7F18FAC434FE51" box="[1032,1141,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Amerilini">Amerilini</taxonomicName>
by Dubatolov (2010) and confirmed by further phylogenetic studies (
<bibRefCitation id="FA3C4B1CFFC1570FAA0C1896C305FE75" author="Zahiri, R. &amp; Holloway, J. D. &amp; Kitching, I. J. &amp; Lafontaine, J. D. &amp; Mutanen, M. &amp; Wahlberg, N." box="[635,836,475,502]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="102 - 124" refId="ref80010" refString="Zahiri, R., Holloway, J. D., Kitching, I. J., Lafontaine, J. D., Mutanen, M. &amp; Wahlberg, N. (2012) Molecular phylogenetics of Erebidae (Lepidoptera, Noctuoidea). Systematic Entomology, 37, 102 - 124. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2011.00607. x" type="journal article" year="2012">
Zahiri 
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAABE1891C2BBFE75" box="[713,762,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FA3C4B1CFFC1570FAB391896C45AFE75" author="Zaspel, J. M. &amp; Weller, S. J. &amp; Wardwell, C. T. &amp; Zahiri, R. &amp; Wahlberg, N." box="[846,1051,475,502]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="101975" refId="ref80173" refString="Zaspel, J. M., Weller, S. J., Wardwell, C. T., Zahiri, R. &amp; Wahlberg, N. (2014) Phylogeny and Evolution of Pharmacophagy in Tiger Moths (Lepidoptera: Erebidae: Arctiinae). Plos One, 9 (7), e 101975. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0101975" type="journal article" year="2014">
Zaspel 
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FABD71891C390FE75" box="[928,977,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FA3C4B1CFFC1570FAC511896C4B9FE76" author="Zenker, M. M. &amp; Wahlberg, N. &amp; Brehm, G. &amp; Teston, J. A. &amp; Przybylowicz, L. &amp; Pie, M. R. &amp; Freitas, A. V. L." box="[1062,1272,475,502]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="348 - 362" refId="ref80274" refString="Zenker, M. M., Wahlberg, N., Brehm, G., Teston, J. A., Przybylowicz, L., Pie, M. R. &amp; Freitas, A. V. L. (2016) Systematics and origin of moths in the subfamily Arctiinae (Lepidoptera, Erebidae) in the Neotropical region. Zoologica Scripta, 46 (3), 348 - 362. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zsc. 12202" type="journal article" year="2016">
Zenker 
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAC0B1891C4F5FE75" box="[1148,1204,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D6B76566FFC1570FA8B018B2C227FD05" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph id="9E1236EDFFC1570FA8B018B2C227FD05" blockId="11.[151,1437,223,646]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FA8B018B2C1AAFD99" bold="true" box="[199,491,511,537]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diversity &amp; Distribution</emphasis>
: In 
<collectingCountry id="E6BA767DFFC1570FAA6F18B2C215FD99" box="[536,596,511,537]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
, tribe 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAAEE18B2C347FD99" box="[665,774,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Amerilini">Amerilini</taxonomicName>
are known by four species of genus 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FACD718B2C5D9FD9A" authority="Walker, 1855" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1855" box="[1184,1432,511,538]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FACD718B2C4BBFD99" box="[1184,1274,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Amerila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="FA3C4B1CFFC1570FAD7718B2C5D9FD9A" author="Walker, F." box="[1280,1432,511,538]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="583 - 775" refId="ref79004" refString="Walker, F. (1855) List of the specimens of lepidopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Vol. 3. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 193 pp. [pp. 583 - 775]" type="book chapter" year="1855">Walker, 1855</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, accounting for 6.06 % of the global 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAA441B6EC2E1FDBD" box="[563,672,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Amerilini">Amerilini</taxonomicName>
moths. Out of the four species, 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAC781B6EC4A1FDBD" authority="(Drury)" baseAuthorityName="Drury" box="[1039,1248,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="astreus">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAC781B6EC4C1FDBD" box="[1039,1152,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. astreus</emphasis>
(Drury)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAD6A1B6EC0A6FDE1" authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1864" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhodopa">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAD6A1B6EC5DDFDBD" box="[1309,1436,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. rhodopa</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
are distributed throughout 
<collectingCountry id="E6BA767DFFC1570FAA601B0AC210FDE1" box="[535,593,583,609]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
whereas, 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAAB61B0AC380FDE2" authority="(Rothschild)" baseAuthorityName="Rothschild" box="[705,961,583,610]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="omissa">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAAB61B0AC36FFDE1" box="[705,814,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. omissa</emphasis>
(Rothschild)
</taxonomicName>
is reported from Himalaya and 
<taxonomicName id="59AD4D6EFFC1570FAD521B0AC153FD06" authority="(Fabricius)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amerila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eugenia">
<emphasis id="ACD9EAFFFFC1570FAD521B0AC5DCFDE1" box="[1317,1437,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">A. eugenia</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
is a species of plains of 
<collectingCountry id="E6BA767DFFC1570FAA521B26C223FD05" box="[549,610,619,645]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
